title: For Sale:  LNIB Burris Eliminator II Laser rangefinding scope
postcontent:
Price drop to $700

Details: http://www.eliminatorlaserscope.com/eliminatorII.html

Looking to maybe sell my Eliminator II. It's only five months old, and comes with the box, caps, and all the manuals and such (including a (not pictured) 4 inch screw-on sun shade for the front that makes it HUGE ;) , along with 2 brand new batteries for it (you'll need these if your range bag is tight and hits the ON button on you...or you can just take out the battery when transporting it). This is a variable 4-12x42 scope with a built in laser rangefinder that works out to 1000 yards, which is very cool. Your lase your target and the distance is displayed at the top and a little illuminated orange dot appears partway down the vertical retical showing the proper holdover at that distance for the specific round you're firing (which you program in beforehand). 

When you're shooting 250 yds with a 223 or 308 and zeroed at 100 yds, you really don't need the laser, but when you move out to 500 or more, its like cheating. :)

See the link above for details and pictures showing how it works.

I paid 899 + shipping. I'm looking to get $700 which is a nice discount. It is in beautiful shape and perfect working order.

I will throw in the 1" quick release riser rail that you see near the bottom of the picture, which I paid $28 for on amazon. Disclaimer: it works fine, but is a bit cheap and a PITA to adjust the tension on, plus it tends to loosen up over time and need to be tightened again (and thus slightly rezeroed). However, I didn't try really *cranking* the adjuster lock nut down or using locktite on it. When it's tight, it does re-zero pretty well when detached and reattached though. Details here: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0024ZS53S/

I also have a Larue QD 5/8" riser rail which you see it mounted on now, but that was like $135 + tax, and it's brand new top quality, so I'd want $130 for that. It's awesome, no creep at all, rezeros perfectly when taken off and reattached. Details here: http://www.laruetactical.com/larue-tactical-picatinny-riser-qd-lt-101

A note about AR-15/AR-10: A riser rail is required if mounting on and AR type rifle because the front lens is huge and protrudes below the mounting rail on the scope (as you can see in the pic). You can tell it was designed to go on a normal hunting rifle like a Remington 700. This also means you'll probably want a 0.75" cheek riser to go with it. You can get one for a Magpul  stock on amazon for $25, or I could maybe be talked out of mine if you need it.

It comes with mounting hardware for a standard rifle though.

I'm selling it because I don't really need it and I kind of want to move to a higher power normal scope, but I do like it and I'm not in a hurry or hurting so DON'T BOTHER with lowball bullshit offers.

I would consider trading for a high quality scope + a bit of cash depending on the value and condition of the trade.

I would be willing to ship if you're willing to risk sending me payment first, but FTF is much preferred for convenience. I have a flexible schedule and can meet almost any time. I will not drive through heavy traffic all the way to South Austin though, we'd have to meet in the middle somewhere. If you're coming from really far, I could maybe be talked into meeting partway for a few bucks more to cover the trouble, depending on the distance.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stainless Desert Eagle .357 Magnum MKI
postcontent:
Here's an interesting piece of Magnum Research history. This is a .357 Magnum Mark I pistol from 1985. It has a 6" Magnaported barrel and Millet adjustable sights (white outline rear and bright orange front). It comes with one stainless mag and one blued mag. Comes with the original box, literature, cleaning rod, brush and gas system scraping tool. The gun has a "stainless' appearance and that's where the story gets interesting.

The Desert Eagle serial numbers began at "3000." The suffix "S" was used for "stainless guns." This pistol is serial 309x - S, making it one of the first 100 "stainless" Desert Eagles to ever be imported into this country. According to Magnum Research, these old guns that were catalogued as "stainless" were actually stainless steel cast frames along with Satin Nickel plated barrels and slides (made of Chromoly steel). This one has black accents and it looks sharp. It handles screaming full-power .357 loads like a champ and recoils like a 9mm pistol. It's a ton of fun to shoot; nobody has shot it without having a huge smile on their face afterwards. Someone in the past 30 years ground down the sharp edge inside the trigger guard on the right side of the frame.

If you're looking for a solid shooter that looks great, this is it! It isn't very common to come across the "stainless" MKI in .357MAG, let alone one with the Millet sights and Magnaport factory upgrades. In fact, it was several years before I came across this one. I think it's safe to call it "rare" but this one is a shooting piece, not a collector's piece.

Sale price of $1200 is FIRM. Sorry, but $1,000 won't cut it. That's the going rate for a regular blued model... WITHOUT adjustable sights or Magnaports! I was born at night, but it wasn't last night!

I would consider trades, plus or minus cash for:
